{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff: prompt/request builder must pass the full taxonomy into the API client payload. A pure unit of one helper could miss wiring bugs where the built field is dropped/renamed before send. Rejected System because behavior text is about request content, not real network/OS effects; rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model judgment, only payload composition.","test_description":"Wire classifier module with a stub API client that records outbound payload. Invoke classify with a known taxonomy and assert the sent request contains every taxonomy label exactly once in the expected field.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at boundary between API response adapter and module return contract. Unit-testing only a normalization helper can miss miswiring where raw provider label bypasses validation. Rejected Agentic using behavior text \"API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy\" because a deterministic stubbed invalid label is sufficient; no model-quality dependence.","test_description":"Use module with stub API response `{label: \"not_a_taxonomy_label\"}` and taxonomy `[legal, technical, financial, other]`. Assert classifier returns `unknown` to caller and never exposes raw invalid label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic normalization logic for one local transformation boundary; no I/O or module handoff is required to expose inconsistency. Rejected Integration because behavior text explicitly scopes to \"normalization step\" with identical raw input.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with identical raw response fixtures (including casing/whitespace variants already normalized by parser) and assert identical output label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live model decisions (\"live API calls\") and consistency of returned labels. Stubs cannot reveal model/output variability or provider-side drift effects. Rejected Workflow because calls are repeated independent classifications, not a multi-stage agent pipeline with chained model decisions.","test_description":"Run N repeated real classifications for the same document+taxonomy against the production-like model endpoint, recording raw provider outputs and normalized labels. Assert label consistency across runs when raw provider response is unchanged; if raw response differs, classify as provider-change case rather than module defect.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is interaction between token-budget enforcement and dispatch gate (truncate/reject then send/do-not-send). Need module wiring, not real network. Rejected System because behavior says \"before dispatch\" and can be validated with in-process client spy; rejected Agentic because no dependence on model output content.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget and use inputs over/under limit. With a stub client, assert over-limit requests follow policy (truncated payload or rejection with no dispatch) and under-limit requests dispatch normally.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Catching real failure requires a real AI provider call because assertion is about provider-reported usage, which stubs can mask. Although this uses real external HTTP, the decisive dependency is AI API behavior/metadata from the model call path, so Agentic is the safer minimum. Rejected Integration due behavior text \"Provider-reported token usage\" which disqualifies purely stubbed testing.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls for representative documents and collect provider usage metadata (`prompt/completion/total` as available). Assert reported total tokens per call do not exceed configured budget; fail on any over-budget live report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry/backoff orchestration around provider errors; deterministic stubbed rate-limit responses are sufficient to expose logic bugs (no wait, wrong retry count, premature failure). Rejected System because real network timing is not required by behavior text; rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model decision quality.","test_description":"Use stub API client that returns rate-limit error (e.g., 429/RateLimit) on first K attempts then success. With controllable clock/timer, assert module waits per policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of bubbling immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
